There can be nothing more frustrating than being stuck in traffic due to lights out because of power cuts. Many people have taken it on themselves to direct traffic in the absence of traffic officers. But, now the JMPD is warning residents against the practice. eNCA speaks to the JMPD's Xolani Fihla. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - The Johannesburg Metro Police Department is warning citizens to abstain from directing traffic during power cuts. READ: Traffic Lights | MEC Mamabolo says power cuts hinder service providers Many people have taken it on themselves to direct vehicles in the absence of traffic officers. However, the JMPD says they are not authorised to do this and the department will not be held liable if anything goes wrong. Watch the video above for more details.